20 nmol/L","10 nmol/L"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe interquartile range (IQR) is calculated by subtracting the first quartile (Q1) from the third quartile (Q3). In this dataset:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EQ3 = 75 nmol/L\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EQ1 = 45 nmol/L\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ETherefore, IQR = 75 - 45 = \u003Cstrong\u003E30 nmol/L\u003C/strong\u003E\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe IQR is a measure of statistical dispersion that represents the range where the middle 50% of the data falls. It is less sensitive to extreme values than the total range.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The interquartile range (IQR) represents the middle 50% of a dataset, calculated as Q3 minus Q1.","Quartiles divide data into four equal parts, with Q1 at the 25th percentile, Q2 (median) at 50th, and Q3 at 75th percentile.","Percentiles indicate the percentage of observations that fall below a given value in a dataset."],"references":["Sullivan LM. Essentials of biostatistics in public health. 3rd ed. Burlington (MA): Jones \u0026 Bartlett Learning; 2018.","Dawson B, Trapp RG. Basic \u0026 clinical biostatistics. 4th ed. New York: McGraw-Hill; 2004."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"56140"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17450"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"56140","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/56140"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-16T13:17:24+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-16T13:18:30+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10140"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"70675"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji"